{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563622"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:01:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:01:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16832"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16832"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.01,0.13,0.02,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70468"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55932"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"8763"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22498"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70468"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of bilateral lower limb weakness and loss of pain sensation below the mid-thoracic region. She has a history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and atrial fibrillation. Her medications include Metformin, Perindopril, and Warfarin. On examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 88/min and irregular, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals complete loss of motor function and pain sensation below T6, but preserved position and vibration sense.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior spinal artery thrombosis","Multiple sclerosis","Central cord haemorrhage","Spinal epidural abscess","Anterior spinal artery thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classical features of anterior cord syndrome - sudden onset bilateral motor weakness and loss of pain sensation with preserved proprioception and vibration sense. The pattern of neurological deficits corresponds to the vascular territory of the anterior spinal artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior spinal artery thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the patient\u0027s vascular risk factors (hypertension, diabetes, atrial fibrillation) and the sudden onset of symptoms. The anterior spinal artery supplies the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, including the corticospinal tracts (motor function) and spinothalamic tracts (pain and temperature sensation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior spinal artery thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E would primarily affect the dorsal columns, resulting in loss of proprioception and vibration sense, which are preserved in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral cord haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a different pattern, often with greater weakness in the upper extremities than the lower extremities, and may include bladder dysfunction. The sudden onset would be compatible, but the pattern of deficits does not fit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E has a gradual onset and would be unlikely to present with this pattern of neurological deficits in this age group. The preservation of proprioception would be unusual in MS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinal epidural abscess\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with fever, back pain, and a more gradual onset of neurological symptoms. The absence of fever or signs of infection makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anterior cord syndrome presents with loss of motor function and pain/temperature sensation below the level of injury, with preserved proprioception and vibration sense.","Aortic dissection and aortic surgical interventions are the most common causes of anterior cord syndrome.","The anterior spinal artery supplies the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, including the corticospinal tracts and spinothalamic tracts."],"references":["Klakeel M, Thompson J, Srinivasan R, McDonald F. Anterior spinal cord syndrome of unknown etiology. Proc (Bayl Univ Med Cent). 2015 Jan;28(1):85-7. doi: 10.1080/08998280.2015.11929201. PMID: 25552812; PMCID: PMC4264724.","Sandoval JI, De Jesus O. Anterior Spinal Artery Syndrome. 2024 Jun 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809566.","Davda N, Osman C. Anterior spinal cord infarct: a rare yet disabling stroke. BMJ Case Rep. 2018 May 7;2018:bcr2017221655. doi: 10.1136/bcr-2017-221655. PMID: 29735490; PMCID: PMC5950573.","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Yogendranathan N, Herath HMMTB, Jayamali WD, Matthias AT, Pallewatte A, Kulatunga A. A case of anterior spinal cord syndrome in a patient with unruptured thoracic aortic aneurysm with a mural thrombus. BMC Cardiovascular Disorders. 2018 Mar 5;18(1)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55932"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16832"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55932"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T14:00:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T19:08:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70468"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i